<P>In calculating these costs, we make the following assumptions.&nbsp; =
For=20
phone lines, we have about a 2.5 kilobyte per second transfer rate at =
$1.50 per=20
minute, which leads to 400 seconds or 6.7 minutes of transfer which is a =
little=20
over $10 per Megabyte. Call set-up and other inefficiencies can increase =
this to=20
$20 per Megabyte.=20
<P>For international roaming services we assume a low quality connection =
of=20
about 1 kilobyte per second (or less) which means 1000 seconds or 17 =
minutes of=20
transfer is needed which is $4 at the low end and up to $10 per Megabyte =
if=20
there are other inefficiencies such as a degraded connection.=20
<P>For private VSAT, the cost would be $10,000 to $20,000 per month for =
a 128=20
kbps private connection typically. This is about $0.23 per minute.&nbsp; =
But at=20
most such a connection would be used at 30% of capacity so we would get =
a=20
transfer rate of&nbsp; 1000 Kilobytes /[(128 kbps/8bits/byte) X 30%] =
=3D&nbsp; 200=20
seconds or 3.3 minutes/Megabyte transfered. This means that for a =
well-utilized=20
line the cost would be about $0.6 per Megabyte transfered.=20
<P>For a leased international voice channel, it is assumed that such a =
line=20
would be provided on a cost recovery basis by the telecom authority. =
With such=20
an assumption the line would be about $2000/month, or about $0.05 per=20
minute.&nbsp; A 64 kbps line can download at about 8 kilobytes per =
second but=20
for a leased connection it would likely be used at less than 30% =
capacity so it=20
would take 1000 Kilobytes/(8 kilobytes/sec X 30%) =3D 400 sec =3D 7 =
minutes or $0.35=20
per Megabyte.=20
<P>So it can be seen that depending on the type of international data=20
connections that is available, and the efficiency with which it is used, =
the=20
cost of transfering data from the Internet to Eritrea can vary by a =
factor of=20
50.=20
<P>Currently, for the email system, the bandwidth costs account for=20
approximately 30% of the retail price of the email services in =
Eritrea.&nbsp;=20
Other costs are effectively the technical service, capital recovery, and =

administrative operational costs of system administration and service =
provision.=20

<H3><A name=3D"Types of Services"></A>Types of Internet =
Services</H3>Different=20
types of Internet use make very different demands on the network. =
Electronic=20
mail (email) makes relatively few demands on the network. The data =
volumes are=20
relatively small (about 20 Megabytes per day for Eritrea as of August =
1999). And=20
if it takes an hour or two for a message to be delivered, it is =
generally OK. It=20
is easy for the network to provide slow data transfer for low volumes of =
data.=20
<P>Meanwhile web-browsing can make significant demands on the network. =
And a=20
single page of information may be 0.1 Megabytes or more. Furthermore =
most people=20
will not want to wait for more than half a minute to minute for the =
information=20
to be displayed on their screens. Only 200 people downloading one page =
each can=20
conceivably require as much data transfer as the entire country's email =
system=20
in one day. And each user may wish to have their data transfered at a =
rate of=20
2-3 kilobytes per second. This can make tremendous demands on a network =
which=20
has a limited international connection.=20
<P>For international web browsing over a limited international =
connection, one=20
must have either very few users, or very slow data transfer (i.e. it may =
take=20
several minutes for a page with a lot of graphics to be displayed). This =
is the=20
fundamental delemma of Internet access in remote locations with limited=20
telcommunications infrastructure.=20
<H2><A name=3DMarket></A>Market Analysis: Who can pay how much, and for=20
what?</H2>Our basic goal in this analysis is to use market and cost =
analysis=20
analysis methods to see how local businesses can&nbsp; implement an =
equitable=20
social objective: "From each according to his ability (<I>to pay for=20
services</I>) to each according to his need (<I>for access to Internet=20
services</I>)."&nbsp; While this slogan may historically have a lot of=20
progandistic baggage associated with it, the idea that those who can pay =
more=20
(for high quality) should pay more than the needy but poorer and less =
pickey=20
sections of the market is just basic fairness.=20
<P>Eritrea's computer communications market is diverse. At one extreme =
are=20
international business people who need to connect at the Internet at =
speeds=20
which are only limited by the modem in their laptop. At the other end =
are poor=20
students for whom 50 Nacfa (US$ 10) per month is a big expense.=20
<P>For business people, their alternative is making an international =
phone call=20
to Europe or the U.S. and connecting to a service provider there. Such a =
call=20
would cost $2-$3 per minute originating from Eritrea and $1-$2 per =
minute=20
originating from outside Eritrea. On such a connection, a user can =
obtain=20
transfer speeds of 2-4 kilobytes/sec. Their main requirement of an =
Eritrean=20
Internet service, would be U.S.-level service at a price that is cheaper =
than=20
the alternative of making an international call to a foreign =
ISP.&nbsp;&nbsp; If=20
our target price is 1/2 the cost of an international dial-up connection, =

then&nbsp; $0.50 to $1.00 per minute is a potentially acceptable price =
for top=20
quality Internet access.=20
<P>For the poor students, their main market demand is acceptable access =
at rock=20
bottom prices.&nbsp; They would probably want at least a few hours of =
Internet=20
use for their hard-earned 50 Nacfa. If we say this corresponds to a =
little over=20
10 minutes per day, then we have 300 minutes for $6, or $0.02 per minute =
of use.=20
And if they get a few hundred pages of information per month, they will =
probably=20
be pretty happy.=20
<P>Therefore, the 'ability to pay' for the different components of the =
Eritrean=20
market varies by a factor by more than an order of magnitude. This is =
simply a=20
reflection of the fact that per-capita incomes in Eritrea are less than =
1/100-th=20
what they are in the wealthier, more technologically developed =
countries.=20
Ideally, an Eritrean Internet can satisfy the different demands of both=20
expatriot and local users.=20
<H2><A name=3DService></A>Service Products: Satisfying Customers and =
Recovering=20
Costs.</H2>
<H3><A name=3D"Current Products"></A>Current Products and =
Services</H3>Currently,=20
in Eritrea there is only one Internet service product: E-mail.&nbsp; =
There is a=20
two-tiered pricing system with selected government institutions =
receiving a low=20
service-level connection for free and other customers receiving email =
services=20
for about $15 to $20 per month from private service providers.&nbsp; The =
free=20
connections provide crucial services for select government ministries =
that do=20
not have a budget to pay, and represent a couple percent of total email =
volume,=20
about 5% to 10% of total users/institutions and about 10% of bandwidth=20
costs.&nbsp; The Research and Training center of the Department of =
Energy=20
provides service and support at no cost to the serviced =
ministries.&nbsp; The=20
national university receives services on a lumped service contract with =
one of=20
the private providers.&nbsp; There is no public service to secondary =
schools,=20
nor any service to public libraries as of yet.=20
<H3><A name=3D"Potential Service Levels"></A>Potential Service Levels, =
Products,=20
and Prices</H3>With the arrival of Internet connectivity, there should =
be both a=20
decrease in bandwidth costs, and a diversification of the potential =
information=20
services and service levels that can be provided to customers/users.=20
<H4><A name=3D"Cheaper Email"></A>Cheaper E-mail</H4>The first potential =
benefit=20
of cheaper international bandwidth for national Internet development =
will the=20
the possiblity of decreasing the cost of basic email services.&nbsp; =
This means=20
that a basic email account will have an international data transfer cost =
of a=20
few dollars&nbsp; per month.&nbsp; It should be possible to therefore =
offer an=20
email-only account with little or no technical support for about $5 per =
month or=20
lower, while offering email-only accounts with technical support for =
about $10=20
per month. These price levels are comparable to those offered in the =
U.S. for=20
such accounts.=20
<P>There will be two main private sector impediments to cheap email-only =

accounts.&nbsp; The first and most important will be that supporting =
such=20
services will compete with full-service Internet accounts for the =
technical=20
support resources within local ISP's.&nbsp; The overhead and profit =
margins on=20
the full-service accounts will be higher than for low-end e-mail only=20
accounts.&nbsp; Given this fact, local ISP's may or may not offer such =
services=20
even if it is strictly economical to do so.=20
<P>Especially for local ISP's that make the commitment to a leased data =
line,=20
their primary objective will be to develop a revenue stream that can =
support the=20
continuing cost of a leased line.&nbsp; If they can charge $20 - $30 for =
a=20
full-service connection, they will put a premium on making sure there =
are enough=20
full service accounts to provide their revenue stream. It therefore may =
be in=20
their interest to shut-out low cost email accounts even if&nbsp; 75% of =
the=20
potential low-cost e-mail users can't afford a full service =
account.&nbsp; The=20
key factor in whether or not very low cost e-mail access is provided in =
Eritrea=20
will depend on there being enough competition between ISP's so that at =
least one=20
of them finds it profitable to provide services to the low-cost email =
market.=20
<P>Over the long term it will be in the interest of local ISP's to =
provide some=20
very low cost access services and to provide free access services to =
students in=20
educational institutions. Market development in Eritrea for computer=20
communications services is growing exponentially with a doubling time of =
6=20
months to a year.&nbsp; Providing low-cost entry into this market will =
allow=20
more people to develop experience in computer network use.&nbsp; The =
lack of=20
experience by local users in computer networks is the primary limitation =
for=20
local demand development. This is because with its very low level of=20
computerization, and its reliance on slower paper-based organization, =
most=20
Eritrean organizations can potentially reap very economical benefits =
from=20
increased levels of computerization.&nbsp; The lack of skilled personnel =
is the=20
primary impediment.=20
<P>Therefore, given rapid, exponential growth of computer comunications =
markets=20
(even in Eritrea), small increases in market expansion now will have=20
exponentially large impacts several years down the line.=20
<H4><A name=3D"Multi-lingual Email"></A>Multi-lingual Email and=20
Internet</H4>Another major barrier to Internet and e-mail use in Eritrea =
is the=20
language barrier.&nbsp; It is actually currently possible to do e-mail =
in=20
Tigrigna and Arabic, but the methods for doing this are not fully known =
in=20
Eritrea.=20
<P>Hyper-Text Mark-up Language (HTML) is rapidly becoming a =
platform-independent=20
standard for formatted documents on the Internet, and this language has=20
multilingual utilities built into its standards.&nbsp; HTML is the =
computer=20
language in which most Internet content is written, and most e-mail =
programs are=20
now capable of writing and displaying messages with HTML =
formatting.&nbsp; In=20
HTML there is a font specification command that sets the font or script =
in which=20
the message is displayed.&nbsp; This is the method by which email =
messages are=20
sent in Chinese, Thai, and a great variety of other languages. The exact =
same=20
methods apply to sending messages and producing web content in Tigrigna =
and=20
Arabic.=20
<P>In addition to the fonts, one needs a method for typing the script =
into the=20
computer.&nbsp; This involves the use of a program that remaps the =
keyboard to=20
produce the proper letter encodings corresponding to what is being typed =
in by=20
the user. Several programs for doing this in Windows are available in =
Eritrea=20
and Ethiopia, including Yada (by Tfanus Enterprises) Ge'ez Gate and a =
host of=20
others.&nbsp; Software for composing messages costs a significant amount =
($90=20
for Yada for example), but the fonts for displaying the result are =
free.&nbsp;=20
This means that it is currently possible and perfectly feasible to =
produce=20
local-language web content.&nbsp; Web sites that have this content, can =
also=20
provide an FTP (file transfer protocol) link for downloading the fonts =
so that=20
anyone can view the content for free.=20
<P>Local language email and web content has a couple of national =
advantages for=20
Eritrea.&nbsp; The first advantage is that it makes the information in =
local=20
languages more accessible to Eritreans who speak and read primarily =
Arabic or=20
Tigrigna.&nbsp; This can dramatically expand the relevance of Internet =
services.=20

<P>The second national advantage of local language Internet content, is =
that it=20
decreases the competative advantage of foreigners with regards to =
utilizing=20
locally produced information content.&nbsp; One disadvantage of =
producing=20
content for the Internet is that the result is often that the =
information is=20
more accessible to someone abroad than it is for someone in the country =
in which=20
it was produced.&nbsp; On the other hand, reports in Tigrigna and Arabic =
will be=20
easier to for Eritreans to write than English reports.&nbsp; And also, =
once=20
posted on the web, it will be far easier for Eritreans to read and =
interpret=20
these documents.&nbsp; Foreigners who want to utilize this information =
will=20
likely have to hire Eritreans to translate and interpret the documents =
for them.=20

<H4><A name=3D"Browsing Locally Available Web"></A>Browsing Locally =
Available Web=20
Content</H4>The cheapest dial-up information service that can be =
provided by=20
ISP's is a dial-up local web browsing service that does not bring any =
new=20
information over International lines except by special order from=20
customers.&nbsp; For such types of customers, they dial into a sever =
that has a=20
large amount of web content on its local hard disk.&nbsp; The cost of =
such a=20
server is perhaps a couple thousand dollars, and one such server can =
provide=20
services to 8 - 32 phone lines.&nbsp; With more than 10-50 customers per =
phone=20
line, the capital cost per customer is potentially as low as $10 per =
customer as=20
long as the marginal cost of new content is near zero.=20
<P>A near-zero marginal cost of&nbsp; web content for these accounts is =
attained=20
by limitting content to what has been retrieved by other users at other=20
times.&nbsp; The storage cost of this content is nearly zero since the =
cost of a=20
10 Gigabyte hard drive is only about $200 or $0.20 per Megabyte.&nbsp; =
This=20
per-megabyte storage cost is very small compared to the cost of =
transferring the=20
data over the international data lines. <BR>&nbsp;=20
<H4><A name=3D"Producing National Intranet"></A>Producing National =
Intranet=20
Services</H4>Wide area networking can also possibly contribute to the =
more=20
efficient distribution of information within Eritrea.&nbsp; Intranet =
services in=20
Eritrea can contribute to more efficient information dissemination, =
database=20
management services, and intra-national administration and reporting.=20
<P>Several government organs are responsible for providing information =
services=20
to other ministries, local governments, and the public.&nbsp; Some of =
these=20
include:&nbsp; Meteorology services who are responsible for weather =
reports and=20
forecasts to other ministries and agencies, the Department of Energy =
which is=20
responsible for energy and electricity system standards, the Ministry of =

Agriculture which is responsible for agricultural forecasting and the=20
distribution of agricultural inputs and extension support services, and =
the=20
Ministry of Construction which is responsible for managing and approving =

construction projects.&nbsp; All of these agencies could use local =
Intranet=20
services to provide an alternative means of publishing reports and =
updates. In=20
many cases, publishing documents on the Eritrean Intranet or making them =

available for download will be cheaper and easier for many types of=20
constituents.&nbsp;&nbsp; Many documents are prepared on computer (often =
in MS=20
Word), and a site that allows such documents to be downloaded can be =
constructed=20
in a matter of minutes on an existing server.=20
<P>Also, if the Internet becomes popular amongst Eritrean ministries and =
both=20
public and private organizations, certain information such as weather =
reports,=20
forecasts, and crop status which is useful for a wide range of =
productive=20
institutions, could be more easily obtained by surfing the local web =
than by=20
visiting the relevant ministry and asking for a printed report which may =
be=20
expensive.&nbsp; National Intranet distribution of some information may =
be more=20
effective than current paper distribution methods in some cases.=20
<P>Another application of local Intranet services is to allow local=20
organizations to engage in networked data collection and information=20
administration activities. A dial-up line to an organizational data =
entry and=20
retrieval interface could be useful for a wide range of local=20
organizations.&nbsp;&nbsp; This is another service that can be more =
fully=20
developed with local Intranet development.=20
<H4><A name=3D"Real-time Browsing of the International"></A>Real-time =
Browsing of=20
the International Internet</H4>Another service that will be one of the =
high=20
priorities of Internet development in Eritrea will be live browsing of =
the=20
International Internet.&nbsp; Live, direct,&nbsp; international Internet =

browsing will be the most expensive computer communications service of =
Eritrea's=20
Internet/Intranet.&nbsp;&nbsp; Live web browsing is what most people =
think of=20
when one talks about Internet in Eritrea, but it should be reserved for =
only the=20
most important information, or for those who can pay the high costs of a =
live=20
connection.=20
<P>A low speed connection with download speeds of about 0.5 kilobytes =
per second=20
will cost at least $0.25 per minute while a higher speed connection with =

download speeds of over 4 kilobytes per second will cost over $1 per =
minute. In=20
addition, 24 hour-per-day real-time browsing will be one of the last =
services to=20
arrive since it is one of the most expensive services to support.&nbsp; =
But for=20
the average user 50% to 80% of web content will already be available on =
a local=20
proxy-server, so for many users there will the the 'appearance' of =
real-time=20
Internet access even when the international Internet connection is =
congested.=20
<H4><A name=3D"Other Services: Voice, Electronic"></A>Other Services: =
Voice,=20
Electronic Info-publication, and more....</H4>The variety of computer=20
information and communications services that are offered by local ISP's =
are=20
essentially limited by only their imagination and the technical human =
resources=20
needed to maintain them.=20
<P>Internet and national Intranet services are perfectly capable of =
providing=20
multi-lingual, voice, sound, and video publication and distribution =
services at=20
reasonable cost.&nbsp;&nbsp; Which of many possible services are =
actually=20
marketable in the Eritrean context remains to be seen.=20
<P>Just to cite on example, it would be perfectly feasible to send voice =

recordings internationally as email attachments. For example when =
efficiently=20
compressed, voice content requires only 8 kilobytes per second of sound. =
This=20
means that one minute of recorded voice can be sent in 480 =
kilobytes.&nbsp; This=20
means than when the per Megabyte cost of data transfers drops below =
about $4, it=20
becomes more economical to send voice recordings via email or Internet =
than it=20
does to send then over phone lines.&nbsp; This opens up the potential of =
sending=20
voice recordings over the Eritrean Internet.&nbsp; And if done right, =
this is a=20
service that all Eritreans could enjoy. <BR>&nbsp;=20
<H2><A name=3D"System Description"></A>Internet System Description: =
Maximizing=20
Efficiency</H2>Efficient Internet services in Eritrea will need =
customized=20
configurations and specialized software tools.&nbsp; These tools include =
the use=20
of the highly customizable Linux operating system, multi-port serial=20
cards,&nbsp; PPP daemons and scripts, apache HTTP server software, SQUID =
web=20
cache, Common Graphics Interface (CGI) scripts written in Perl that =
interact=20
with customized web forms, the SMAIL mail transport agent, UUCP over =
dial-up and=20
TCP, a customized batched, compressed transport that we call UUCBSMTP, =
and=20
Tigrigna and Arabic language script utilities for clients.=20
<P>It should be noted that other technical solutions besides what is =
being=20
described here exist. In particular, both Microsoft and Sun Microsystems =
provide=20
commercial computer networking solutions for ISP's.&nbsp; But given the =
Eritrean=20
desire for self sufficiency and the need to preserve precious foreign =
exchange=20
dollars, it is likely that the free software solutions that the ETE is =
promoting=20
and developing for use with inexpensive PC's will out-compete standard=20
commercial solutions based on Windows NT or Sun servers.=20
<H3><A name=3DLinux></A>Customizing with Linux</H3>Detailed =
customization of=20
Internet servers at low cost is generally not available with commercial =
Windows=20
NT or Sun Microsystems servers.&nbsp; ETE therefore promotes the use of =
the=20
Linux operating system in order to provide economical, highly =
customized, and=20
efficient transport of data over expensive data links.=20
<P>Linux is free, and installs readily on any personal computer with a =
386=20
processor or above.&nbsp; Recently, a fairly user friendly release of =
Linux=20
called Redhat has become popular and allows one to install the system =
fairly=20
simply. For more detailed information on the Linux operating system the =
reader=20
should refer to more definitive websites such as <A=20
href=3D"http://www.linux.org/">http://www.linux.org/</A>=20
<H3><A name=3D"Serial Cards"></A>Multiport Serial Cards and Dial-up=20
Ports</H3>Multiport serial cards together with a bank of phone lines =
that are=20
configured in a 'hunt group' provide a cheap and efficient means of =
computer=20
dial-up access to Internet services.=20
<P>&nbsp;A hunt group is a collection of several phone lines that can be =

accessed with one phone number.&nbsp; At the telephone company, the =
switch is=20
configured to attempt to connect to the phone lines in sequence.&nbsp; =
If the=20
first number is busy the switch automatically switches the call to the =
next=20
available line.&nbsp; Hunt group phone line configuations are currently=20
available in Eritrea and are currently being used by local ISP's for =
dial-up=20
access.&nbsp; The hunt group configuration allows fewer phone lines to =
be used=20
at greater average capacity for call-in users, using existing phone=20
infrastructure at greater capacity and efficiency.=20
<P>The current volume of computer communications customers in Eritrea is =
still=20
in the hundreds.&nbsp; The number may double every six months to a year, =
meaning=20
that for the next several years the number of customers will remain =
below a few=20
thousand.&nbsp;&nbsp; So assuming that up to 1,000 customers may use one =
ISP and=20
about half of these use the connection for web surfing in addition to =
email, we=20
can calculate the approximate number of phone lines required.&nbsp; If =
each=20
web-surfing customer uses the service an average of half an hour during =
an eight=20
hour day (this low use volume per customer can be enforced by having a=20
significant connection time fee) then an ISP might need as much as 30 =
phone=20
lines.&nbsp;&nbsp; Over the long-term a substantial capacity for running =

multiple phone lines into Eritrean ISP's will need to be developed.=20
<P>At earlier stages of development, ISP's can configure a server with 4 =
to 32=20
dial-in&nbsp; phone lines&nbsp; by using a multiport serial card that =
can=20
connect to a&nbsp; bank of external modems (see for example: <A=20
href=3D"http://www.comtrol.com/sales/specs/rocket.htm">http://www.comtrol=
.com/sales/specs/rocket.htm</A>=20
).&nbsp; The modem that we have had the best experience with in Eritrea =
is the=20
U.S. Robotics Courier V.Everything modem.&nbsp;&nbsp; The larger, more =
expensive=20
(about $200) V.Everything modems appear to have better performance in =
the face=20
of long international line latency, high phone noise levels, and phone =
line=20
unreliability.&nbsp; When the number of phone lines coming into an ISP=20
approaches several dozen, then more advanced technologies for bringing =
bundles=20
of phone lines (or digital phone lines) may need to be investigated. But =
for the=20
time being., multiport serial cards and individual external modems are =
easy to=20
implement and can be customized in their operational qualities and =
parameters in=20
Linux.=20
<H3><A name=3DPPP></A>PPP Daemons and Scripts</H3>The typical dial-up =
networking=20
protocol that is used for connecting to the Internet over phone lines is =
the=20
Point to Point Protocol (PPP).&nbsp;&nbsp; The server-side programs that =
manage=20
the PPP connection for both dial-up users and for the server connection =
to=20
outside Internet are becoming more fully featured.=20
<P>Some of the features of a PPP 'daemon' program that allow for more =
efficient=20
utilization of dial-up connections includes on-demand features that =
allow the=20
server to make an international network connection only when it is =
actually=20
needed by an ISP's customers or a business/government institution, a=20
configurable activity time-out, and the ability to run completely =
customized=20
scripts at the beginning and end of the connection session.&nbsp; =
Customized=20
connection establishment and termination scripts allow for complete =
control and=20
setting up logging and billing systems along with access restrictions =
for=20
different types of user services. <BR>&nbsp;=20
<H3><A name=3DApache></A>Apache HTTP Server</H3>Apache HTTP Server is a =
set of=20
software that allows individuals to set up web servers freely under =
Linux and=20
other operating systems.&nbsp; This allows any business or ISP in =
Eritrea to=20
configure a web server with a regular PC (and therefore a cost of as =
little as=20
$1000).&nbsp; This web server software is efficient can be fully =
customized=20
allowing the same machine to service several web sites at the same time, =
and=20
allowing for the use customized error messages, and dynamic web page =
scripts and=20
programs.&nbsp; Training ISP's and computer businesses in Eritrea in the =

configuration, and use of web server software will allow the use and=20
establishment of local Internet and Intranet servers and sites with =
minimal=20
equipment and software cost impediments.=20
<H3><A name=3DSQUID></A>SQUID Web Cache</H3>For many of Eritrea's =
incipient=20
Internet users, they will be interested in much of the same material =
from the=20
Internet.&nbsp; New posting, community bulletin board postings, and =
basic,=20
practical information pages are likely to be popular.&nbsp; For Internet =
content=20
that may be viewed more than once, there is no need to bring that =
content over=20
the International wires more than once.&nbsp; Because of this, it is =
useful to=20
have a server in Eritrea that keeps copies of the Internet pages that =
have been=20
received and to send users the copies of the pages instead of retrieving =
the=20
page several times.&nbsp; The increased efficiency of retrieving =
multiply viewed=20
pages only once makes it imperative to utilize proxy servers in Eritrea =
which=20
have this capability.&nbsp; SQUID is a standard, freely available web =
caching=20
software, which like other Linux-based software can be installed on a PC =
for=20
essentially free (more about SQUID can be seen at: <A=20
href=3D"http://squid.nlanr.net/Squid/Users-Guide/">http://squid.nlanr.net=
/Squid/Users-Guide/</A>).&nbsp;=20
SQUID efficiently keeps a database of web page copies on the local hard =
drive of=20
the server, and uses an efficient page management protocol to provide =
the=20
duplicate requests of data off the hard disk rather than fetching it =
from the=20
Internet.&nbsp; The details of web caching are complicated by the =
prevalence of=20
dynamic web content, but for that portion of Internet content that is =
relatively=20
static, web caching can drastically increase the efficiency of use of =
the=20
international data connections. <BR>&nbsp;=20
<H3><A name=3D"Web Site Mirroring"></A>Web Site Mirroring and the wget=20
command</H3>Another tool that can be used in increasing the efficiency =
and local=20
hosting of web content is mirroring of&nbsp; the international web =
content that=20
is most of interest to Eritreans. By fetching copies of web pages during =
low use=20
times, the information can be available on the local server and can be =
accessed=20
by Eritreans with no additional data retrieval costs and without&nbsp;=20
international data transfer delays. The wget command in Linux can be =
used to=20
flexibly copy the most interesting content according to a pre-determined =

schedule and load it on the local server. The wget command even has the=20
capability of checking the date of the page being requested and not =
fetching=20
those pages that have not been updated.&nbsp; If used with care to =
develop local=20
information sites that retain the interest of Eritrean Internet users, =
this=20
technique has the potential of increasing the efficiency of information=20
distribution and international bandwidth utilization several fold. =
