proprietary software.&nbsp; Those two elements will allow for =
wide-spread=20
multi-lingual access.=20
<H3><A name=3D"Developing Local Content"></A>Developing Local =
Content</H3>Another=20
very imporant feature of Eritrea's incipient Internet will be developing =
locally=20
useful, relevant and interesting content.&nbsp; Every kilobyte that is =
retrieved=20
by Eritreans from local sites and content is a kilobyte that is not =
transfered=20
over an international communication wire that is using precious foreign =
exchange=20
for its financial maintenance.=20
<P>Development of local content requires allowing a diversity of users =
and=20
developers to post content on their own web sites and providing an =
easy-to-use=20
interface to allow people to do such web content development.&nbsp; In =
terms of=20
increasing the customer base, and the local demand of Internet =
services.&nbsp;=20
It actually might be to the benefit of local ISP's to provide automated =
web=20
hosting services for their users for little or no extra charge for =
Internet user=20
accounts. Even more beneficial for local ISP's would be to organize =
contests=20
amongst their users so that those with the most visits receive some =
reward like=20
free Internet services for one to several months.&nbsp; By providing a =
user=20
friendly interface for local users to upload web content, one allows the =

creation of a pool of potentially hundreds of Eritrean web authors =
rather than=20
just utilizing an elite of a few technical staff working at the local =
ISP's.=20
<H3><A name=3DCGI></A>CGI and Customized, Interactive Web Pages</H3>The =
common=20
graphic interface (CGI) standard for web pages allows one to write =
programs at=20
the server that can dynamically interact with the users that are getting =
web=20
content from the server.&nbsp; By learning how to write CGI scripts and=20
programs, technical workers at Eritrea's ISP's can potentially design =
and=20
implement customized Intranet solutions for a diverse set of Eritrean=20
information networking needs.&nbsp;&nbsp; But since this is a fairly =
advanced=20
skill and there is a derth of experienced programmers in Eritrea, it is=20
uncertain to what extent dynamic web content development will take hold =
in=20
Eritrea.=20
<H3><A name=3DSMAIL></A>SMAIL, UUCP over TCP, and UUCBSMTP</H3>For some =
years to=20
come, email will remain the workhorse and the most popular service =
provided by=20
Eritrea's Internet.&nbsp; UUCBSMTP (Unix to Unix Compressed Batched =
Simplified=20
Mail Transfer Protocol) will remain for some time to come, the most =
efficient=20
way to transfer email volume over the international connection.&nbsp; =
But as=20
more continuous connections to the International Internet become more =
common,=20
the transfers will switch from a international phone calls to taking =
place over=20
a transmission control protocol (TCP) connection over the =
Internet.&nbsp; UUCP=20
(Unix to Unix Copy) will remain a more efficient method for transfering =
batched=20
mail transfers over a slow connection than making mail deliveries =
directly from=20
Eritrea using the Simplified Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).&nbsp; But at =
some=20
point there will be unutilized international bandwith and the efficiency =
of mail=20
transfers over the international connection will become less of a =
concern.&nbsp;=20
At that point,&nbsp; mail transfers will probably be made directly using =
SMTP=20
rather than UUCBSMTP.=20
<H2><A name=3DConclusions></A>Conclusions</H2>
<P><BR>Internet services will arrive in Eritrea in the fall of 1999, =
shortly=20
before the new millenium.&nbsp; It is uncertain if the Eritrean branch =
of the=20
International computer internetwork will be the elite domain of computer =
saavy=20
foreigners or an accessible tool for national economic =
development.&nbsp; For=20
friends of Eritrea, it is certainly important for Internet and computer=20
information services to be accessible to as many Eritreans as possible =
at very=20
cheap prices.&nbsp; But the cost of data services depends not only on an =

inexpensive international connection, but it also depends on the =
ingenuity in=20
innovations of&nbsp; Eritrean ISP's in managing data transfers, local =
hosting of=20
foreign content, and the development and expansion of local =
content.&nbsp; How=20
much ISP's can direct users to content that is already present on the =
hard disk=20
of a local server will determine the cost of Internet access for =
Eritreans as=20
much if not more than the cost of international connectivity.=20
<P>The degree to which the Internet becomes relevant and accessible for=20
Eritreans will depend on the ingenuity, inspiration and dedication of =
both=20
Eritrea's friends and computer and business professionals in =
Eritrea.&nbsp; The=20
ETE hopes to contribute to information accessibility for =
Eritreans.&nbsp;=20
Information access must not become the monopoly domain of a few affluent =

foreigners.&nbsp; The Internet is a public resource, and the public in =
every=20
country and at every income level should have the right and the means to =
access=20
it. <BR>&nbsp;=20
